explanation:
UT_EntryKey_t — must know the underlying type of FuncKey to determine whether comparisons (StubPtr->FuncKey == SearchKey) are integer/opaque keys or pointers to char (C-strings). If it is a char* or similar, memcmp/string comparison rules could apply.

UT_EntryType_t — needed to know the type of EntryType to verify that EntryType comparisons are non-string (enum/integer) rather than pointer/string comparisons.

UT_ENTRYTYPE_UNUSED — needed to confirm the sentinel value used in the code path that sets SearchKey = 0; understanding this constant clarifies whether SearchKey becomes a string pointer (NULL) or numeric 0.

UT_StubTableEntry_t — the struct definition is required to see the exact types of the fields accessed (EntryType, FuncKey). This is the primary symbol to prove the function does or does not perform string comparisons.

UT_StubTable — the array declaration (type and any qualifiers) confirms the element type and that &UT_StubTable[Idx] yields a pointer to the struct with the expected field types.

UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS — its definition (value and type) is needed to confirm the arithmetic and array-indexing behavior; while not directly related to memcmp, it helps verify there is no hidden macro or type trick that would change the meaning of indexing or modulo operations into pointer/string operations.

UT_MaxStubSearchLen — its type and semantics are needed to confirm SearchLimit/SearchLen logic does not involve string lengths or memcmp-like behaviour; also to ensure SearchKey is not reused/overloaded as a pointer to string elsewhere.

Together these symbols let an analyst determine whether any of the comparisons in UT_GetStubEntry are string comparisons (or could hide memcmp use) and thus whether the MISRA rule about memcmp on null-terminated strings could be violated.
